          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"> Intermediate Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">Volcanic Ladies</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><table width='73' border='0' cellspacing='0' cellpadding='0'><tr><td background='/magination/gfx/5star.gif'><img src='/lotr/gfx/trans.gif' width='1' height='25'></td></tr></table><font size=1>(3.63)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=30019">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347">Daniel "Dartax" Burke</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> I am trying to return to my &quot;roots&quot; in Cald. Magam, Flamesmith starts things off, with Nara and Vorga supporting.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> August 14, 2003</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <a href="javascript:card_browser(379)">Magam</a>, Flamesmith<br />
(Starting: Gorgle&#8217;s Glasses)<br />
<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(542)">Nara</a><br />
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(539)">Magma Jile</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(393)">Thermal Blast</a>)<br />
<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(677)">Vorga</a><br />
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(386)">Scroll of Fire</a>)<br />
<br />
Creatures:<br />
Coal <a href="javascript:card_browser(537)">Er<a href="javascript:card_browser(377)">Gar</a></a> x3<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(537)">Er<a href="javascript:card_browser(377)">Gar</a></a> x3<br />
Flambit x3<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(672}<a href="javascript:card_browser({516)">Gia</a>nt <a href="javascript:card_browser(394)">Arboll</a></a> x3<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(365)">Greater <a href="javascript:card_browser(374)">Vaal</a></a> x3<br />
Inferno <a href="javascript:card_browser(337)">Xyx</a> x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(539)">Magma Jile</a> x1<br />
Spark Chogo x3<br />
<br />
Spells:<br />
Brushfire x2<br />
Crushing Heat x3<br />
Fireball x2<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Gift x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(393)">Thermal Blast</a> x1<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(790)">Beam of Light</a> x2<br />
<br />
Relics:<br />
Abraxin&#8217;s Crown x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(545)">Blast Gloves</a> x2<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Glasses x1<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(386)">Scroll of Fire</a> x2   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Total Cards = 40<br />
(Oops! Thankfully, I could "edit" the strategy).<br />
<br />
The first deck I ever posted on DeckTech was a Cald deck. In fact, I used to play Cald so heavily that I was well-known for it. However, I seem to have drifted about the regions and lost my touch with that inner firestorm. Perhaps, this deck might help me rekindle that bonfire.<br />
<br />
Magam, Flamesmith goes first for a very simple reason. She starts with a nice relic for card draw in a Cald deck, and her effect should provide some extra energy to work with. This might help counter the problems with a Cald deck burning itself out. Also, her effect serves two quick purposes. First, it can recoup the energy spent on Gorgle&#8217;s Glasses with interest for each turn you play at least one creature. Secondly, it can setup your use of Gorgle&#8217;s Glasses as well. This magi is quite powerful. I saw her potential early on, but I was too fascinated by the idea of a Boomstick deck (all three magi with an energize of six) to make this Cald deck until more recently. Goodbye, Boomstick. Hello, Magam.<br />
<br />
Nara is one of my favorite Cald magi. Decent energize, and she can really annoy those non-Cald decks out there. See Ergar. No touch the Ergar! Okay, now that is out of my system.... Nara is simply the protection magi of this deck. Still, she&#8217;s not to be underestimated either. There is only one Magma Jile in the deck to make sure she had at least one creature to annoy the opposition with. However, try and hold at least one Ergar for Nara. Ergar is a fun Cald powerhouse creature, and it is very common for an opponent to desire its destruction. This is where Nara&#8217;s protection becomes very handy. Also, if you manage it, the ideal start for Nara would actually be two Ergar and two Giant Arboll&#8211;this is part of why I don&#8217;t think Giant Arboll should&#8217;ve been &#8220;altered.&#8221; Since Giant Arboll no longer discards itself by moving all of its energy (can only move up to six now), abuse it by using the two copies of Spark each creature you control now has. Quickly, you can add six to one Ergar and six to Nara. Toss down some more spells, and you have a really nasty opening move. I haven&#8217;t pulled this off yet, but I shudder at its potential.<br />
<br />
Vorga starts with the Scroll of Fire. Okay, she has a nice power as well. By this time you should have a Brushfire in the discard pile, so her power stacked with the Brushfire and the Scroll of Fire should make mincemeat of most problems. In many ways, I am fond of Vorga and consider her to better than many rare Cald magi. She&#8217;s still one of the best in my book. However, only use her power to remove the more &#8220;deadly&#8221; opposing relics. Otherwise, use it on their creatures instead.<br />
<br />
Coal Ergar is in here to sit under Nara&#8217;s control and waggle its tongue at the opposition. If you are trying to be more serious, then use Core Grag or Wildfire. Or, here&#8217;s a thought... combo the Coal Ergar with Ergar. In this case, use the Spark granted by Ergar to &#8220;shrink&#8221; its cousin. With a smaller Coal Ergar, you are more likely to hit across their swarm and ignore stuff like Stumbling Junjertrug, Tranquility, Arderian-Guard Wings, and so forth, even Burrow. It certainly isn&#8217;t a cure-all, as this trick isn&#8217;t easy to pull off. There are two problems I&#8217;ve noticed so far with this trick. First, their creatures are usually toasted too frequently to make this worthwhile. Second, Coal Ergar is too big. Strange to say something like this about a four energy creature?<br />
<br />
Okay, Ergar combos with Coal Ergar.... However, it also combos with a great many creatures in this deck. Easily one of the better Cald creatures, here&#8217;s a few tricks to consider. Use Spark off any of these creatures before using their own powers&#8211;Flambit, Inferno Xyx, and Spark Chogo. Ha! For two energy (with an Ergar in play), you can &#8220;destroy&#8221; a five energy Pylofuf in one turn. Simply use Spark from the Spark Chogo with a Scroll of Fire and Ergar in play, then use its own power, Fade Away&#8211;umm, let me recalculate that for a six energy Pylofuf.<br />
<br />
Here&#8217;s a possible Flambit trick to consider. Play a Greater Vaal with Magam, Flamesmith. Two extra energy, yes? It won&#8217;t die from its own power, so follow up with a Flambit if possible. Unless they take action against the Greater Vaal, can you see another dice roll coming next turn?<br />
<br />
Okay, and the most powerful combo in deck? Ergar and Giant Arboll. Yes, ladies and gentlemen, the commons rule! Mix in a Scroll of Fire for extra pyrotechnics.<br />
<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Gift and Crushing Heat are two of my favorite spells to use Blast Gloves with. Too bad Blast Gloves can&#8217;t work when targeting magi. Oh, well. Replace Abraxin&#8217;s Crown with Intensify if you wish. Mostly, the crown is in here for hand protection&#8211;strangely, this is to oppose one of my own decks using Storm of Fishes&#8211;and maybe to give a larger angle on those creatureless decks.<br />
<br />
Now, there is one last spell I would like to discuss briefly, Beam of Light. I used to use Raxis for relic removal. A lot more fun, and combined nicely with a lot of other tricks. However, I learned quickly what a Cald Shadow Geyser can do. Ouch! Magam, Flamesmith can sort of ignore this a bit with her effect. Still, that shadow geyser will shutdown a Cald creature deck far more than I could care for. It doesn&#8217;t hurt that Beam of Light also helps against Olabra, so it has been a nice change for my Cald decks. Preferably, use Crushing Heat to deal with opposing relics and save Beam of Light for creatures and spells.<br />
<br />
As for how the deck has worked so far, I can&#8217;t really say much other than it destroyed at least one swarm deck using only Magam, Flamesmith. After that game, my opponent and I agreed that Magam can beat Tryn easily, because she did&#8211;plus two other Naroom magi beforehand. And, what made it interesting was that I started with a real bad opening hand and spent more energy in the opening couple turns trying to pull something out of that disaster, and Magam still took Wence, Poad, and Tryn out (in that order).<br />
<br />
In keeping with my decks posted on DeckTech, here&#8217;s some possible swaps for the rare or limited cards in this deck.<br />
<br />
Greater Vaal &#8212; Flame Rudwot<br />
Inferno Xyx &#8212; Drakan<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Gift &#8212; Sulfurous Spirit<br />
Gorgle&#8217;s Glasses &#8212; Tomorrow&#8217;s Jewel<br />
Scroll of Fire &#8212; Rayje&#8217;s Sword*<br />
<br />
*I don&#8217;t really think the deck needs Rayje&#8217;s Sword as it is, but if you lose one or more Scroll of Fire it could become more crucial. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/magination/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=30019"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=30019" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/magination/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></td></tr></table></td>
